   296‚Üí### Infer the matching types from a pattern
   297‚Üí
   298‚Üí#### `P.infer<typeof pattern>`
   299‚Üí
   300‚ÜíTS-Pattern is pretty handy for parsing unknown payloads like HTTP responses. You can write a pattern for the shape you are expecting, and then use `isMatching(pattern, response)` to make sure the response has the correct shape.
   301‚Üí
   302‚ÜíOne limitation TS-Pattern had in its previous version was that it did not provide a way to get the TypeScript type of the value a given pattern matches. This is what `P.infer<typeof pattern>` does :)
   303‚Üí
   304‚Üí```ts
   305‚Üíconst postPattern = {
   306‚Üí  title: P.string,
   307‚Üí  description: P.optional(P.string),
   308‚Üí  content: P.string,
   309‚Üí  likeCount: P.number,
   310‚Üí};
   311‚Üí
   312‚Üítype Post = P.infer<typeof postPattern>;
   313‚Üí// Post: { title: string, description?: string, content: string, likeCount: number }
   314‚Üí
   315‚Üíconst userPattern = {
   316‚Üí  name: P.string,
   317‚Üí  postCount: P.number,
   318‚Üí  bio: P.optional(P.string),
   319‚Üí  posts: P.optional(P.array(postPattern)),
   320‚Üí};
   321‚Üí
   322‚Üítype User = P.infer<typeof userPattern>;
   323‚Üí// User: { name: string, postCount: number, bio?: string, posts?: Post[]  }
   324‚Üí
   325‚Üíconst isUserList = isMatching(P.array(userPattern));
   326‚Üí
   327‚Üíconst res = await fetchUsers();
   328‚Üí
   329‚Üíif (isUserList(res)) {
   330‚Üí  // res: User
   331‚Üí}
   332‚Üí```
   333‚Üí
   334‚Üí### New type specific wildcards
   335‚Üí
   336‚Üí#### `P.symbol`
   337‚Üí
   338‚Üí`P.symbol` is a wildcard pattern matching any **symbol**.
   339‚Üí
   340‚Üí```ts
   341‚Üímatch(Symbol('Hello'))
   342‚Üí  .with(P.symbol, () => 'this is a symbol!')
   343‚Üí  .exhaustive();
   344‚Üí```
   345‚Üí
   346‚Üí#### `P.bigint`
   347‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
